docs.abstract: Protests of conservatives speakers at colleges have prompted new policies that penalize disruptions, putting academia on the front lines of the left-right culture wars.
docs.snippet: Protests of conservatives speakers at colleges have prompted new policies that penalize disruptions, putting academia on the front lines of the left-right culture wars.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the Board of Regents of the University of Wisconsin wanted to address the issue of free speech on campus last fall, it adopted a three-strikes policy that is the strictest of its kind: Any student found to have disrupted the free expression of others is expelled after a third infraction.

headline.main: In Name of Free Speech, States Crack Down on Campus Protests
headline.print_headline: In Name of Free Speech, a Crackdown on Campus Protests

docs.abstract: Across the country, some candidates are shouting for gun restrictions they would once have advocated in whispers, if at all.

docs.lead_paragraph: AURORA, Colo. — When the Columbine High School massacre happened near here in 1999, many felt it would galvanize gun control efforts. Others thought the same in 2012, when a gunman killed 12 moviegoers at a midnight screening of “The Dark Knight Rises.”

headline.main: Bearing F’s From the N.R.A., Some Democrats Are Campaigning Openly on Guns
headline.print_headline: Not Afraid to Claim An F From the N.R.A.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Early Thursday morning, less than 24 hours after Justice Anthony M. Kennedy announced his retirement, scores of conservative leaders and grass-roots strategists dialed into a conference call to gear up for their most significant Supreme Court nomination battle in decades.

docs.abstract: Brian Kemp and Stacey Abrams are both trying to avoid a runoff in Georgia’s rancorous campaign for governor. Polls suggest they may get one anyway.
docs.snippet: Brian Kemp and Stacey Abrams are both trying to avoid a runoff in Georgia’s rancorous campaign for governor. Polls suggest they may get one anyway.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — Georgia’s campaign for governor neared an end on Monday as the state prepared to render its judgment in a contest long imbued with undercurrents of race and history, and freshly roiled by a swirl of allegations about election security.

headline.main: Georgia Governor’s Race Is Hurtling Toward Election Day, and Passions Are Rising
headline.print_headline: Passions Rise in Georgia As the Governor’s Race Hurtles Toward the Tally

docs.abstract: Mobilized by the nation’s divisions on race and Donald Trump’s presidency, black women are using networks forged in segregation to turn out voters this fall.
docs.snippet: Mobilized by the nation’s divisions on race and Donald Trump’s presidency, black women are using networks forged in segregation to turn out voters this fall.
docs.lead_paragraph: AMERICUS, Ga. — Lorena Barnum Sabbs thought the past really was past. Born 67 years ago in a segregated hospital, she was arrested when she was 11 for trying to integrate the local movie theater and locked in a stockade for several days without beds, working toilets or running water. Later, as one of the first black girls to attend the formerly whites-only high school, she ventured to the bathroom only in groups for fear of attacks.

headline.main: Driven by South’s Past, Black Women Seek Votes and a New Future
headline.print_headline: Looking for Voters and a New Future, Driven by the South’s Past

docs.abstract: Paulette Jordan, a long-shot candidate for governor in a deep-red state, would be the first female governor there and the first Native American governor anywhere.
docs.snippet: Paulette Jordan, a long-shot candidate for governor in a deep-red state, would be the first female governor there and the first Native American governor anywhere.
docs.lead_paragraph: EMMETT, Idaho — This state is indisputably Trump country, what with the president’s 32-point victory margin in 2016 and the Republican state leadership and congressional delegation. Still, in storefront windows like at the Possumtrot Traders pawnshop in this deeply conservative town of 6,800, you see it: a large Paulette Jordan sign displayed next to a Trump sign.

headline.main: Idaho Isn’t Turning Blue, but One Democrat Is Turning Heads
headline.print_headline: Winning Idaho? Unlikely. But She Is Turning Heads.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — With a brutal finality, the extent of the Republicans’ collapse in the House came into focus last week as more races slipped away from them and their losses neared 40 seats.

headline.main: Despite Big House Losses, G.O.P. Shows No Signs of Course Correction

docs.abstract: Mr. Poliquin, a two-term congressman from Maine’s Second District, lost re-election, adding to widespread Republican losses in the Northeast.
docs.snippet: Mr. Poliquin, a two-term congressman from Maine’s Second District, lost re-election, adding to widespread Republican losses in the Northeast.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jared Golden, a Marine Corps veteran and Democratic state lawmaker in Maine, defeated New England’s lone House Republican, Bruce Poliquin, on Thursday, just two days after Mr. Poliquin filed a lawsuit to stop the counting of votes under the state’s new ranked-choice voting system.

headline.main: Maine’s Bruce Poliquin, Lone Republican in House From New England, Loses Re-election
